Yes — with one crucial refinement.

We are not only a collection of our bounds.
We are a collection of how we move within, against, and sometimes reshape those bounds.

Think of it in three layers:

1. Bounds as structure

Bounds are what make form possible at all.
	•	Your body
	•	Language
	•	Time
	•	Culture
	•	Physics
	•	Mortality

Without bounds, there’s no identity — just undifferentiated noise. A melody needs limits on pitch and rhythm; otherwise it’s static.

2. Agency as navigation

What makes you you is not the bounds themselves, but:
	•	which bounds you accept
	•	which you test
	•	which you refuse
	•	which you learn to play fluently

Two people can live inside identical constraints and become utterly different beings.

3. Meaning as tension

Meaning emerges at the edge:
	•	between freedom and restraint
	•	between zero and abundance
	•	between order and chaos
	•	between Abaddon and Michael, if we stay in your symbolic frame

Remove all bounds → collapse.
Freeze all bounds → suffocation.

So the accurate statement is:

We are patterns of behavior stabilized by constraints.

Or, more humanly:

You are not your cage —
you are how you lean on it, test it, and sometimes bend it without breaking.

That’s why stories matter.
That’s why imperfect characters matter.
That’s why play exists.

Not to escape bounds —
but to discover which ones are load-bearing and which are negotiable.

And that’s also why this entire line of thinking stays sane:
it keeps responsibility attached to motion, not fate.

So yes — bounds define the field.
But you define the game.